# Auth & Email Conventions

## Token Strategy — Access + Refresh
- **Access token** (short-lived, default `15m`) → response body, sent by clients as `Authorization: Bearer ...`. Secret: `JWT_ACCESS_SECRET`, TTL: `JWT_ACCESS_EXPIRES_IN`.
- **Refresh token** (long-lived, default `30d`) → httpOnly cookie scoped to `/api/v1/auth`. Secret: `JWT_REFRESH_SECRET`, TTL: `JWT_REFRESH_EXPIRES_IN`.
- Both JWTs carry only `{ userId, type }` — role and profile come from the DB in `protectedRoutes`.
- `utils/jwt.js` exports `generateAccessToken`, `generateRefreshToken` (returns `{ token, expiresAt }`), `verifyAccessToken`, `verifyRefreshToken`.

## Refresh Token Storage (`RefreshToken` model)
- One document per active session: `{ user, tokenHash (SHA-256, unique), expiresAt (TTL index), userAgent, ip, revokedAt }`.
- Never store the plain token. Hash with `crypto.createHash('sha256').update(token).digest('hex')`.
- The TTL index on `expiresAt` lets Mongo purge expired rows automatically.

## Rotation + Reuse Detection
Every call to `POST /auth/refresh-token` must:
1. Verify the JWT with `verifyRefreshToken`.
2. Look up `{ tokenHash: sha256(token) }`. If **missing or revoked** → treat as reuse: revoke every non-revoked token for that user, clear the cookie, return 401.
3. Otherwise: mark the current row `revokedAt: now`, issue a new access+refresh pair via `issueTokens`, set the new cookie.

## Cookie Helper (`utils/cookie.js`)
- `REFRESH_COOKIE_NAME = 'refreshToken'`, path `/api/v1/auth`.
- Always `httpOnly: true`, `sameSite: 'lax'`, `secure: NODE_ENV === 'production'`.
- Use `setRefreshCookie(res, token, expiresAt)` and `clearRefreshCookie(res)` — never set/clear the cookie by hand.

## Auth Middleware (names matter)
- `protectedRoutes` — access-JWT gate (`verifyAccessToken`), attaches the full Mongoose user doc to `req.user`, rejects if `!user.active` or `passwordChangedAt > iat`.
- `allowTo(...roles)` — authorization gate.
- Use `req.user._id`, not `req.user.id`.

## Login
Return the **same** error message for unknown email and wrong password (`'Incorrect email or password'`) to prevent user enumeration. Only after password verification should you surface account-state errors (deactivated, etc.).

## Signup / Login / Reset Password
Each returns `{ user: toPublicUser(user), accessToken }` and sets the refresh cookie via the shared `issueTokens(user, req, res)` helper. `resetPassword` additionally revokes every existing refresh session — changing a password must log the user out on all devices.

## Logout
`POST /auth/logout` is **unauthenticated**. Reads the refresh cookie, marks the matching DB row `revokedAt`, and clears the cookie. An expired access token must not prevent logout.

## Password Reset (link-based)
- `forgetPassword` → generate `crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('hex')`, store **SHA-256 hash** in `passwordResetToken`, set `passwordResetExpires` (60 min). Email `${CLIENT_URL}/reset-password/<plainToken>`.
- `resetPassword` at `POST /reset-password/:token` → validate `newPassword === confirmPassword`, hash the URL token, look up user by hash + unexpired, save the new password (pre-save hook re-hashes), clear both reset fields, revoke all refresh sessions, issue a fresh token pair.
- On email-send failure, **roll back** the reset fields so the user can retry immediately.

## Email Utility
- `utils/email.js` default export: `sendEmail({ email, subject, html, text? })`.
- Transport: Gmail via `EMAIL_USER` + `EMAIL_PASS` (App Password).
- HTML templates live in `src/utils/emailTemplates/`. Each file default-exports a function returning an HTML string. Use **inline CSS + tables** for Outlook/Gmail compatibility.

## Controller Conventions
- Always wrap handlers with `asyncHandler`.
- Wrap external calls (mail send) in a narrow `try/catch` only when a **compensating DB action** is required.
- Return a `toPublicUser` shape (`{ id, email, role, name }`) from any endpoint that returns a user — never the raw document.
